Likely root cause: a check-then-act race around the expired-token path.

At `src/auth/rate_limiter.ts:42`, if the code does something like:

```ts
if (token.isExpired()) {
  scheduleRefresh(token)
}
```

then two concurrent refresh requests can both read the same expired state before either request records that refresh work is already pending. Because the “expired?” check and “mark/schedule refresh” step are not atomic, both callers proceed and enqueue duplicate refresh jobs.

The fix is usually to introduce single-flight behavior around refresh scheduling:

```ts
let refreshPromise: Promise<Token> | null = null

function refreshOnce() {
  if (!refreshPromise) {
    refreshPromise = doRefresh().finally(() => {
      refreshPromise = null
    })
  }

  return refreshPromise
}
```

or, if this is per-user/per-token, a keyed in-flight map:

```ts
const inFlightRefreshes = new Map<string, Promise<Token>>()
```

Important detail: the in-flight marker must be written synchronously before any `await` or async scheduling boundary, otherwise the same race remains.

